## 2) Prevent bulk from overwhelming DB/API

### A) In-processor dependency throttles
Even with worker limiter, individual job handlers may fan out too aggressively. Add explicit per-resource throttles:

```ts
import pLimit from 'p-limit';

const dbLimit = pLimit(20);      // max concurrent DB-heavy operations/process
const httpLimit = pLimit(50);    // max concurrent outbound API calls/process

async function processBulk(job: any) {
  const items: string[] = job.data.itemIds;

  await Promise.all(
    items.map((id) =>
      dbLimit(async () => {
        const row = await loadRow(id);
        return httpLimit(() => sendWebhook(row));
      })
    )
  );
}
```

### B) Separate connection pools
Give bulk workers smaller DB pool or isolated read replicas:

- critical DB pool: reserved capacity (e.g., 20)
- standard: moderate (30)
- bulk: capped (15) + read replica usage

### C) Queue pausing on backpressure
If DB latency breaches threshold, auto-pause bulk queue:

```ts
import { Queue } from 'bullmq';
const qBulk = new Queue('jobs:bulk', { connection, prefix });

async function backpressureGuard(dbP95Ms: number) {
  if (dbP95Ms > 250) {
    await qBulk.pause();
  } else {
    await qBulk.resume();
  }
}
```

Run this in a control loop every 15–30s.

